05249nam a22008055i 9780824862251DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20062007hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248622517 a10.1515/97808248622512doi  a(DE-B1597)484118  a(OCoLC)1024048566  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aNB1912.B83bM43 2007 7aART0260002bisacsh04a730.951/181 aMcNair, Amy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDonors of Longmen :bFaith, Politics, and Patronage in Medieval Chinese Buddhist Sculpture /cAmy McNair. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2006] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b86 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOne. Emperor as Tathāgata -- tTwo. The Mechanics of a Karmic Gift of Sculpture -- tThree. The Rhetoric of Expenditure -- tFour. The Politics of Filial Piety -- tFive. Cīnasthāna Preserves the Dharma -- tSix. Rouge and Powder Money -- tSeven. The Satellite Grottoes -- tEight. Salvation for One -- tEpilogue: The Later Life of the Site -- tAppendix: Chinese Texts of Longmen Inscriptions -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDonors of Longmen is the first work in a Western language to re-create the history of the Longmen Grottoes, one of China’s great stone sculpture treasure houses. Longmen, a UNESCO World Heritage site located near the old capital of Luoyang in modern Henan Province, consists of thousands of ancient cave chapels and shrines containing Buddhist icons of all sizes that were carved into the towering limestone cliffs from the fifth to the eighth centuries. Beyond its superb sculpture, Longmen also preserves thousands of engraved dedicatory inscriptions by its donors, who included emperors and empresses, aristocrats, court eunuchs, artisans, monks, nuns, lay societies, female palace officials, male civil and military officials, and ordinary lay believers.Based on wide reading of both Asian and Western-language scholarship and careful analysis of the architecture, epigraphy, and iconography of the site, Amy McNair provides a rich and detailed examination of the dynamics of faith, politics, and money at Longmen, beginning with the inception of the site at Guyang Grotto in 493 and concluding with the last major dated project, the forty-eight Amitabhas added to the Great Vairocana Image Shrine in 730.Through her sensitive and well-informed exploration of Longmen’s huge repository of remarkable early sculpture, McNair gives voice to a wide array of medieval believers, many of them traditionally excluded from history. Hers will be the definitive work on Longmen for years to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArt patronagezChina. 0aBuddhist art and symbolismzChinazLongmen Caves. 0aBuddhist gods in art. 0aBuddhist sculpturezChinazLongmen Caves. 0aSculpture, ChinesezChinazLongmen CavesyTang-Five dynasties, 618-960. 0aSculpture, ChinesezChinazLongmen CavesyThree kingdoms-Sui dynasty, 220-618. 7aART / Sculpture & Installation.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486225140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824862251423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824862251.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013 